issues.title: ListeningGenerator needs better thought out behaviour
issues.body:
The ListeningGenerator has several undefined behaviours:
- If a value hasn't yet been consumed, then next() returns null, which cannot be distinguished from consuming a null value and returning that.
- If multiple values have been consumed, then only the most recent is returned by next(), meaning some values will be lost.

Some suggestions to address this:
- next() could block until at least one value has been consumed.
- next() could throw an exception if no values have yet been consumed.
- consume(...) could throw an exception if more than one value is consumed.
- Generator could maintain a queue of generated values, and pop and return items in next().
- Generator could maintain a collection of generated values, and return a randomly selected value on next().

I don't know what behaviour you intended, or what it should really do, but I don't think the current implementation is it.

All the behaviours could probably be justified in different contexts, so maybe there should be multiple listening generators, or a builder to correctly configure one.

- enhance Generators interface to support `map`, `flatMap`, `foreach`,  `take`, `peek`,  ... using default methods on Generators Interface
- Support conversions from/to Java 8 `Stream` and `Supplier`
- Support runtime configuration of the backing java `Random` generator

`takeWhile` is generalization of the the take/limit. I admit there is no easy way of implementing it as so far the only implementation I can think of is based on pre-fetching next value to find out whether generation should end which requires all the actions in the upstream chain (towards the 'root' generator)  to be without side effects as otherwise some actions may be executed after the end of the generation (similar to some guava implementations).

Also takeWhile does not need act on the generated values. It can be used to stop generation on some external conditions like time (stop generation after certain time) so it is valid in certain cases even for random generators
